restrict it to only start when the proposal.status === 'approved' and otherwise
throw an error (do not allow transitions from 'proposed', already 'in_progress',
or terminal states). In the startExecutionWithWorker function, check
proposal.status and if it's not 'approved' throw an Error like "Task {taskId}
not approved for execution"; only then set proposal.status = 'in_progress',
update proposal.assignedWorkerId and proposal.execution.startedAt, persist the
proposal in this.proposals, and create the this.executions entry (startedAt,
workerId, attempts) — this prevents double-dispatch and avoids overwriting
existing execution records for tasks not approved.
